\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. L. camara} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 627 (1753). Up to 1·5 m, with a strong, unpleasant smell. Young twigs 4-angled, sometimes prickly, pubescent. Leaves 5-8 cm, ovate, serrate, rugose, more or less hairy, petiolate. Inflorescences axillary; peduncles about equalling the subtending leaves. Corolla yellow or orange, usually changing to red; tube 7-8 mm; limb 4-5 mm in diameter. Drupe globose, black, distinctly longer than calyx.{\i  Naturalized in Acores, and perhaps in parts of the Mediterranean region, where it is frequently cultivated for ornament.} [Az ?Hs Si.] ({\i Tropical and warm-temperate America; widely naturalized in the tropics and subtropics.})
