\pard\f0\fs28  Several American species, as well as their hybrids, are grown in European gardens and sometimes escape. Among them,{\b  V. canadensis} (L.) Britton,{\i  Mem. Torrey Bot. Club}{\b  5}: 276 (1894) ({\i V. aubletia} Jacq.), from E. North America, and{\b  V. perunana} (L.) Druce,{\i  Rep. Bot. Exch. Club Brit. Is. }{\b 3}: 425 (1914) ({\i V. chamaedryfolia} Juss.), from South America, are locally naturalized in Germany and the latter also in E. France (near Strasbourg). {\i V. canadensis} has pinnatipartite to 3-fid leaves and shortly pedunculate spikes elongating in fruit, with crowded, large and showy flowers in shades of blue, purple or white. {\i V. peruviana} has crenate to incise-dentate leaves and long-pedunculate spikes with crowded, large and showy, bright scarlet to pink flowers; both are perennial herbs.
